412→                           A theorem of Sylvester and Schur (see <a href="#cite-Er34-683" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er34','683'); return false;">[Er34]</a>) states that $P(\binom{n}{k})&gt;k$ if $k\leq n/2$. Erdős <a href="#cite-Er55d-683" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er55d','683'); return false;">[Er55d]</a> proved that there exists some $c&gt;0$ such that, whenever $k\leq n/2$,\[P\left(\binom{n}{k}\right)\gg k\log k.\]Erdős <a href="#cite-Er79d-683" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er79d','683'); return false;">[Er79d]</a> writes it 'seems certain' that this holds for every $c&gt;0$, with only a finite number of exceptions (depending on $c$). Standard heuristics on prime gaps suggest that the largest prime divisor of $\binom{n}{k}$ is, for $k\leq n/2$, in fact\[&gt;e^{c\sqrt{k}}\]for some constant $c&gt;0$. <br><br>This is essentially equivalent to <a href="/961" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[961]</a>.
